Recent taxonomic contributions to our knowledge of the tribe can be found in Brailovsky (2009 ; key to
Phthia Stål, 1862
complex), Brailovsky (2014a ; key to
Leptoglossus Guérin-Méneville, 1831
), Brailovsky (2014b ; key to
Holhymenia Lepeletier & Serville, 1825
), Brailovsky (2016 ; key to
Anisoscelis Latreille, 1829
) and Coscarón & Pall (2015 ; Anisoscelini of Argentina ). Additionally, faunistic and distributional papers on Coreidae such as Garcete-Barrett (2016 ; Paraguay checklist), Maes & Ĝllner-Scheiding (1993; Nicaragua checklist), Linares & Orozco (2017 ; Honduras checklist), and Brailovsky and Perez-Gelabert (2019 ; key for Hispaniola) have expanded our knowledge of Anisoscelini . Additionally, recent phylogenetic analysis foretells the eventual revision of the tribe (
Forthman et al. 2020
).

